    <!-- ══════════════ §4.2 VAULT MANAGEMENT ══════════════ -->
    <div class="dp-section" id="vault-management">
      <div class="dp-section-header">
        <div class="dp-section-num">§4.2</div>
        <h2>Vault Authorization &amp; Management</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="dp-callout dp-ok" style="margin-bottom:24px;">
        <span class="dp-ci">🔐</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Mandatory requirement.</strong> Every CBDC issuance requires an active, authenticated Vault.
          Assets cannot be exported via email or SFTP unless they have been successfully staged in a Vault
          environment. Operators can manage vaults via the <strong>Vaults menu</strong> or directly within
          the <strong>Issuance Desk properties panel</strong>.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>What is a Vault?</h3>
      <p>
        In bearerCORE™, a Vault is not a folder — it is a cryptographically secured staging environment
        for national assets before they are distributed to commercial banks. Each vault is an AES-256-GCM
        encrypted <code>.svlt</code> file that wraps the CBDC note bundle during the minting and transfer
        pipeline. A vault must be created and authenticated before any batch can be exported or delivered.
      </p>

      <h3>Vault Management — Menu Access</h3>
      <p>
        The <strong>Vaults</strong> menu in the application menu bar is the primary management surface.
        It is a top-level menu item, signalling to operators that vault management is a high-privilege
        task separate from routine operations.
      </p>

      <div class="dp-table-wrap"><table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Menu Item</th><th>Shortcut</th><th>Function</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>New Vault…</strong></td>
            <td><kbd>⌃⌥⌘V</kbd></td>
            <td>Creates a new encrypted <code>.svlt</code> staging file. Operator sets vault name, encryption mode (AES-256-GCM), key length, and passphrase. The vault file is written to the configured output path.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Open Vault…</strong></td>
            <td><kbd>⌃⌥O</kbd></td>
            <td>Decrypts and mounts an existing vault for inspection or for use in an active issuance session. Requires the vault passphrase.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Import Vault…</strong></td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>Securely ingests a vault file from an SFTP endpoint or a physical hardware security token. Used when a vault was created on another workstation and must be transferred to the current one.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><em>separator</em></td>
            <td></td>
            <td></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Save Copy of Vault…</strong></td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>Exports an encrypted backup of the active vault to a chosen destination. Required for disaster recovery and audit archive obligations.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Delete Vault…</strong></td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>Permanently destroys a vault and its staging contents after confirmed issuance. Irreversible. Requires operator confirmation.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table></div>

      <h3>Vault Management — Issuance Desk (Inline Access)</h3>
      <p>
        Since a vault is required for issuance, the Issuance Desk right pane includes a
        <strong>Vault Authentication</strong> section (§5.F) with an inline vault selector.
        This prevents operators from having to navigate away from the issuance workflow if
        they discover the target vault has not yet been set up.
      </p>
      <div class="dp-table-wrap"><table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Required</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Vault Name</td><td>Yes</td><td>Dropdown of pre-configured vault identifiers on the workstation. Selecting a vault auto-populates Mode, Key Length, and Block Size.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Password</td><td>Yes</td><td>Vault encryption passphrase. Never stored — used at runtime only to authenticate the vault session.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Confirm Password</td><td>Yes</td><td>Must match Password exactly. Client-side validation prevents mismatched auth attempt.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Output Path</td><td>Auto</td><td>Filesystem path where the encrypted bundle will be written. Auto-populated from vault config on vault selection.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Mode</td><td>Auto</td><td>Encryption cipher — e.g. AES-256-GCM. Loaded from vault config.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Key Length</td><td>Auto</td><td>Encryption key size in bits. Loaded from vault config.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Block Size</td><td>Auto</td><td>Block/padding size. Loaded from vault config.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table></div>

      <div class="dp-callout dp-danger">
        <span class="dp-ci">⛔</span>
        <div>
          The <strong>Vault Authenticated</strong> readiness check in the Transfer Readiness Checklist
          (§5.E) must be green before Transfer Ownership is enabled. A vault that exists but has not been
          authenticated in the current session is treated as unauthenticated.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Vault Lifecycle in an Issuance</h3>
      <div class="dp-flow">
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>1. Pre-issuance — Create or Open Vault</h4>
          <p>Before starting an issuance, the operator creates a new vault (<strong>Vaults → New Vault…</strong>) or opens an existing one (<strong>Vaults → Open Vault…</strong>). The vault name will appear in the Issuance Desk vault selector.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>2. Issuance Desk — Authenticate Vault</h4>
          <p>In the right pane Vault Authentication section, the operator selects the vault from the dropdown and enters the passphrase. This sets the <em>Vault Authenticated</em> readiness check to green.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>3. Export — Bundle Staged in Vault</h4>
          <p><strong>Export send bundle</strong> encrypts the CBDC note package using the authenticated vault key and writes it to the vault output path. No delivery occurs at this stage.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>4. Transfer — Delivered from Vault</h4>
          <p><strong>Transfer Ownership</strong> sends the staged bundle from the vault output path to the claiming institution via Email or SFTP. All four readiness checks — including Vault Authenticated — must be green.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>5. Post-transfer — Archive or Delete Vault</h4>
          <p>After confirmed delivery, the operator either saves a backup (<strong>Vaults → Save Copy of Vault…</strong>) for audit archive, or destroys the staging vault (<strong>Vaults → Delete Vault…</strong>) to close the issuance environment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <%# ── §4.2.1 Post-Transfer Integrity Check ──────────────────────────── %>
      <h3 id="vault-integrity">Post-Transfer Integrity Check (Import Vault)</h3>
      <p>
        When a CBDC vault is transported to a recipient workstation via SFTP, the file is
        <em>in flight</em> and vulnerable to interception or silent corruption. A bit-level
        alteration to an encrypted vault cannot be detected by simply opening it — the AES-GCM
        tag will reject the ciphertext, but this gives the operator no forensic context.
        The <strong>Post-Transfer Integrity Check</strong> runs before the vault is ever mounted,
        enforcing a full cryptographic handshake in five sequential stages.
      </p>

      <div class="dp-callout dp-ok" style="margin-bottom:24px;">
        <span class="dp-ci">🔑</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Automatic trigger.</strong> Selecting <strong>Vaults → Import Vault…</strong>
          always opens the Integrity Check modal first. The vault passphrase is only requested
          after <em>all five stages pass</em>. There is no way to bypass this gate.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h4>File Pair Convention</h4>
      <p>
        Every SFTP transfer must include <strong>two files</strong> — the vault and its companion
        manifest. bearerCORE™ automatically looks for the manifest file in the same directory,
        with the same base name and a <code>.manifest</code> extension:
      </p>
      <div class="dp-table-wrap"><table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>File</th><th>Type</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><code>Vault_GHA_2026.svlt</code></td>
            <td>Vault</td>
            <td>AES-256-GCM encrypted CBDC note bundle</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><code>Vault_GHA_2026.manifest</code></td>
            <td>Manifest</td>
            <td>JSON file containing the vault's cryptographic fingerprint and origin signature</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table></div>

      <h4>Manifest File Schema</h4>
      <p>The <code>.manifest</code> file is a JSON document generated and signed by the sending workstation at the point of export:</p>
      <pre style="background:#0D2A4A;color:#C9E8FF;border-radius:4px;padding:16px;font-size:11px;overflow:auto;">{
  "vault_file":           "Vault_GHA_2026.svlt",
  "sha256":               "&lt;hex-encoded SHA-256 of raw .svlt bytes&gt;",
  "sha512":               "&lt;hex-encoded SHA-512 of raw .svlt bytes&gt;",
  "sender_public_key":    "&lt;hex-encoded 32-byte Ed25519 public key&gt;",
  "signature":            "&lt;hex-encoded 64-byte Ed25519 sig over SHA-256 digest&gt;",
  "created_at":           "2026-04-21T10:00:00Z",
  "transfer_window_hours": 48
}</pre>

      <h4>The Five-Stage Validation Flow</h4>
      <div class="dp-flow">
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>Stage 1 — Manifest Location</h4>
          <p>bearerCORE™ searches for <code>{vault_stem}.manifest</code> in the same directory as the selected <code>.svlt</code> file. If the manifest is absent or unparseable, validation fails immediately and the vault is quarantined. This prevents any attempt to import a vault without a verifiable chain of custody.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>Stage 2 — SHA-256 Hash Verification</h4>
          <p>A fresh SHA-256 hash is computed over every byte of the <code>.svlt</code> file and compared against the manifest's <code>sha256</code> field. If even a single bit changed during SFTP transfer — due to corruption, truncation, or tampering — the hashes will not match and the vault is quarantined.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>Stage 3 — SHA-512 Hash Verification</h4>
          <p>An independent SHA-512 digest is computed and compared. Providing a second hash from a different digest family eliminates the theoretical risk of a preimage attack designed to defeat only one algorithm. SHA-512 is optional in the manifest; if absent, this stage passes automatically.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>Stage 4 — Origin Signature Verification (Ed25519)</h4>
          <p>The manifest carries a 64-byte Ed25519 digital signature over the raw 32-byte SHA-256 digest. bearerCORE™ verifies this signature using the <code>sender_public_key</code> from the manifest (via libsodium <code>crypto_sign_verify_detached</code>). A valid signature proves the vault was created by the holder of the corresponding private key — the authorised sending workstation. No other entity can forge this signature without the sender's private key.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dp-step">
          <h4>Stage 5 — Transfer Window (Timestamp Anchoring)</h4>
          <p>The manifest's <code>created_at</code> timestamp is compared against the current UTC time. If the vault is older than <code>transfer_window_hours</code> (default: 48 hours), the import is rejected as a potential <strong>replay attack</strong> — a scenario in which an attacker re-sends an old, cryptographically valid vault to trigger a duplicate issuance. Manifests dated more than 5 minutes in the future (clock skew) are also rejected.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h4>UI Workflow — Integrity Check Modal</h4>
      <p>
        The Integrity Check modal opens immediately when the operator selects Import Vault.
        It is a blocking modal — no other action can be taken until it completes.
      </p>
      <div class="dp-table-wrap"><table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Phase</th><th>Display</th><th>Outcome</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Scanning</strong></td>
            <td>Gold progress bar advances; each stage row shows "Computing…" in amber</td>
            <td>Operator observes live progress — no interaction required</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Stage Pass</strong></td>
            <td>Row turns green: e.g. "SHA-256 matches registry manifest ✔"</td>
            <td>Next stage begins automatically after 400 ms</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>All Pass</strong></td>
            <td>Progress bar turns green; success panel: "All cryptographic checks passed"</td>
            <td>Operator clicks <strong>Continue</strong> → passphrase prompt appears</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Stage Fail</strong></td>
            <td>Row turns red; quarantine panel expands with full alert message</td>
            <td>Vault is blocked; incident logged; operator clicks <strong>Acknowledge</strong></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table></div>

      <h4>Tamper Detection — Emergency Quarantine Mode</h4>
      <p>
        If any stage fails, bearerCORE™ enters Emergency Quarantine mode:
      </p>
      <ul style="margin:0 0 16px 24px; line-height:1.8;">
        <li><strong>Hard Block:</strong> The vault file is flagged and cannot be opened, inspected, or mounted — even if the operator possesses the correct passphrase.</li>
        <li><strong>Automated Incident Report:</strong> An <em>Inbound Transport Violation</em> record is automatically filed via <code>POST /api/v2/audit/inbound_transport_violations</code>. The record appears in the <strong>Fraud Dashboard</strong> under the "Inbound Transport Violations" category.</li>
        <li><strong>High-Contrast Alert:</strong> The modal displays: <em>"Security Alert: Vault Integrity Compromised. File does not match source signature."</em> with the specific failure reason.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="dp-callout dp-danger">
        <span class="dp-ci">⛔</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Never dismiss a quarantine alert without investigation.</strong>
          An integrity failure on an inbound vault indicates either network corruption, an
          SFTP interception event, or an attempted vault replay. Treat every Inbound Transport
          Violation as a security incident. Escalate to the Central Bank Security Operations team
          and preserve the <code>.svlt</code> and <code>.manifest</code> files as forensic evidence.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h4>API — Inbound Transport Violations</h4>
      <div class="dp-table-wrap"><table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Endpoint</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><span class="badge" style="background:#1B5E20;color:#fff;padding:1px 6px;border-radius:3px;font-size:10px;">POST</span></td>
